    slug: 'confluence-vs-coda',
    analysis: `Confluence vs Coda is the knowledge management and team wiki comparison — Atlassian's established documentation platform vs Coda's modern all-in-one doc that blends wikis with databases and apps.

Confluence (Atlassian, acquired 2004, launched originally 2004): Confluence is the enterprise-standard team wiki and knowledge management platform — used by 60,000+ organizations including major enterprises. Confluence's strengths: deep Jira integration (the world's most-used project management tool), mature enterprise features (space permissions, advanced admin controls, audit logs), decades of battle-tested stability, and the largest library of third-party integrations and macros (1,000+ via Atlassian Marketplace). Confluence is the default documentation platform for software development teams that use Jira. Confluence Cloud is the modern hosted version; Confluence Data Center/Server is for on-premises deployments. Pages, Spaces (departments/teams), and Templates are the core concepts. Pricing: Free (10 users), Standard $5.75/user/month, Premium $11/user/month, Enterprise custom. Weakness: can feel dated compared to newer tools; the editor is less polished than Notion or Coda; large Confluence instances become difficult to search/navigate.

Coda (founded 2014, launched 2019): Coda is a next-generation document platform that combines rich text docs with tables (databases), automations, and building blocks — closer to a no-code app builder than a traditional wiki. Coda's core concept: a Doc can contain multiple pages, but those pages can embed powerful tables with custom views (grid, kanban, calendar), formulas (like Excel functions), buttons, and automations. Coda Pack integrations (500+) allow pulling in live data from Slack, Jira, GitHub, Salesforce, etc. Coda AI writes content, summarizes pages, and can interact with doc data. Pricing: Free (limited docs), Pro $10/doc-maker/month, Team $30/doc-maker/month (unlimited editors are free — only "Doc Makers" pay). Coda is popular at product-led companies (Spotify, Uber, Square use Coda). Weakness: smaller enterprise customer base vs Confluence; less proven at very large scale; Jira integration less native than Confluence.

Verdict: Confluence is the enterprise-standard for Jira-centric engineering orgs and large companies needing governance and admin controls. Coda is the modern choice for product teams wanting flexible database-docs, lightweight app building, and a better editing experience. Many orgs migrating from Confluence to Notion or Coda cite the richer editing experience and better doc-database flexibility.`,
