    slug: 'sweden-vs-norway',
    analysis: `Sweden vs Norway is the Scandinavian country comparison between two of the world's wealthiest, most livable, and most progressive societies — with significant differences in natural resources, culture, and outdoor landscapes.

Sweden (population 10.5M, GDP $660B): Sweden is Scandinavia's largest country by population and the Nordic region's economic and cultural center. Stockholm is a major European tech hub (home to Spotify, Klarna, Mojang/Minecraft, King, iZettle, and dozens of unicorns — Europe's "Silicon Valley of gaming"). Sweden's economy: manufacturing (Volvo, IKEA, H&M, Ericsson, Scania), pharmaceuticals (AstraZeneca), banking (SEB, Handelsbanken), and tech. Swedish welfare state: universal healthcare, free university education, 480 days parental leave (Sweden pioneered gender-neutral parental leave), and some of the world's most generous social systems. Culture: design-centric (IKEA effect), egalitarian (Jante Law cultural principle), and progressive on social issues. Geography: southern Sweden (Skåne) is gentle farmland; northern Sweden (Lapland) is arctic wilderness. Swedish language is mutually intelligible with Norwegian and Danish. Climate: colder winters than you'd think for latitude (Gulf Stream influence is less than Norway).

Norway (population 5.5M, GDP $700B): Norway has a higher GDP per capita than Sweden (over $100K) due to its sovereign wealth fund — the Government Pension Fund Global at $1.6T (the world's largest sovereign wealth fund), funded by oil revenues from the North Sea. Norway's oil fund means every Norwegian citizen is effectively a millionaire on paper. Norway is not a full EU member (EEA member). Natural wonders: Norway has the world's most dramatic fjord coastline — Geirangerfjord, Nærøyfjord (UNESCO World Heritage), Aurlandsfjord, Hardangerfjord. The Northern Lights (Aurora Borealis) are best viewed from northern Norway (Tromsø, Lofoten Islands). Lofoten Islands are among the world's most photogenic archipelagos. Capital Oslo has excellent quality of life and cultural institutions. Norway has among the world's highest costs of living. Economy: oil/gas, fishing (salmon — Norway is #1 global farmed salmon exporter), shipping, hydropower (98%+ of electricity from renewables), and maritime industries.

Verdict: For natural landscape and outdoor adventure (fjords, Northern Lights, hiking), Norway is unmatched. For cultural/tech innovation, urban European quality of life, and social systems with broader global influence, Sweden is the more internationally impactful country. Both have extremely high HDI rankings and quality of life scores.`,
